User should be able to:

choose columns (including UDFs)
filter dynamically
group & aggregate
sort
export

WITHOUT writing SQL.

Example UI action:

Columns: segment, risk_score
Filter: risk_score > 70
Group By: segment
Aggregation: AVG(risk_score)

Engine generates safe SQL automatically.

🧠 Core Principle

⚠️ NEVER allow users to generate SQL directly.

Instead:

User builds Report Definition (metadata) → Engine converts → SQL.

🏗️ Architecture Overview
Report Builder UI
        ↓
Report Definition (JSON)
        ↓
Query Validator
        ↓
Metadata Resolver
        ↓
SQL Generator
        ↓
Execution Engine
        ↓
Result Formatter
✅ Step 1 — Report Definition Model

User selections are stored as structured JSON.

Example:

{
  "entity": "customer",
  "columns": ["segment"],
  "aggregations": [
    {"field": "risk_score", "func": "AVG"}
  ],
  "filters": [
    {"field": "risk_score", "op": ">", "value": 70}
  ],
  "group_by": ["segment"],
  "sort": [{"field":"segment","dir":"ASC"}],
  "limit": 100
}

This is the only input to query generation.

✅ Step 2 — Metadata Registry (Safety Layer)

Create table:

reportable_fields
-----------------
field_name
source_column
data_type
is_aggregatable
is_filterable
entity

Example:

field	column	type
risk_score	risk_score	number
segment	segment	text

This prevents arbitrary SQL usage.

✅ Step 3 — Validation Phase ⭐ (Most Important)

Algorithm:

Validate Fields
for field in request:
   ensure field exists in metadata

Reject unknown fields.

Validate Aggregations

Example rules:

Type	Allowed
number	SUM, AVG
text	COUNT only
date	MIN, MAX
Validate Operators

Whitelist only:

=  !=  >  <  >=  <=  IN  BETWEEN  LIKE

Never allow raw SQL fragments.

Validate Limits

Prevent heavy queries:

limit <= MAX_ALLOWED_ROWS
group_by count <= 5
✅ Step 4 — SQL Construction (Safe Builder)

We DO NOT concatenate strings blindly.

We build query parts.

4.1 SELECT Clause

Algorithm:

select_parts = []

Columns:

select_parts += group_by fields

Aggregations:

select_parts += FUNC(column) AS alias

Example result:

SELECT segment, AVG(risk_score) AS avg_risk_score
4.2 FROM Clause

Always fixed:

FROM customer_reporting

User never controls this.

4.3 WHERE Clause (Parameterized)

⚠️ Always use bind parameters.

Algorithm:

WHERE risk_score > :p1

Parameters:

p1 = 70

Never inline values.

4.4 GROUP BY Clause

Auto-generated:

GROUP BY segment

Only from validated fields.

4.5 ORDER BY Clause

Whitelist fields only:

ORDER BY segment ASC
4.6 LIMIT/OFFSET

Controlled pagination:

LIMIT 100 OFFSET 0
✅ Step 5 — Final Generated Query

Result:

SELECT
   segment,
   AVG(risk_score) AS avg_risk_score
FROM customer_reporting
WHERE risk_score > $1
GROUP BY segment
ORDER BY segment ASC
LIMIT 100;

Parameters:

[70]

Safe. Fast. Predictable.

✅ Step 6 — Execution Layer

Execution rules:

read-only DB connection
timeout enforced
memory limit enforced

Example:

query_timeout = 10 seconds
✅ Step 7 — Result Formatting

Engine converts SQL result → UI format:

{
  "columns": ["segment","avg_risk_score"],
  "rows": [
     ["gold",82.4],
     ["silver",71.2]
  ]
}

Supports:

table view
charts
CSV export
Excel export
🔒 SQL Injection Protection Strategy

You achieve safety via:

Layer	Protection
Metadata registry	whitelist columns
Operator whitelist	restrict expressions
Parameter binding	safe values
Fixed FROM clause	no joins injection
Aggregation rules	prevent misuse

User NEVER touches SQL.

⚡ Performance Controls (Enterprise Tricks)
1️⃣ Query Complexity Scoring

Before execution:

score =
  filters * 1 +
  group_by * 5 +
  aggregation * 3

Reject if too complex.

2️⃣ Auto Index Recommendation

Track frequent queries:

segment + risk_score

Suggest index automatically.

3️⃣ Result Cache

Cache identical report definition hash:

hash(report_json)

Reuse results.

4️⃣ Async Execution for Heavy Reports

If estimated rows > threshold:

run background job
notify when ready
